27.10.2018

Read the file Cust_churn This dataset contains information about telecommunication company customers behavior The dataset includes information about: Customers who left within the last month - the column is called Churn The number of weeks since the subscription_variable name is Account Length The number of text messages (Message), number of minutes spent on day time, evening, night and for international calls in respective variables, The number of times a customer calls the call center (Callcenter enquiry) The variables Call.Plan and Message.Plan indicate whether the customer has subscription to call plan and/or message plan.

churn <- read.csv("Cust_churn.csv")

The main objective of this assignment will be building models which will predict the customer churn (meaning that a customer stops using the services of this telecom company) as accurately as possible.

(1 point) Check if the classes of the variables are correctly understood by R, if not, change the types of the factor variables.

churn$Churn <- factor(churn$Churn, levels = c(0,1), labels = c("No", "Yes"))

churn$Message.Plan <- factor(churn$Message.Plan, levels = c(0,1), labels = c("No", "Yes"))

(7 points) if the customer has the following characteristics: DayMins=260, EveMins=150, Call.center.Enq=10, does not have message and call plans, have not made any international calls and messages and the account length is 20. Looking at the decision rules, what is the probability that a customer may churn? use the coeficients to calculate the same probability using the logistic regression model. See whether there are significant differences and make comment.

prob <- exp(-8.2137089676 + 0.0004362439*20 + 0.0480655065*0 + 0.0123030656*260 + 0.0063869952*150 + 0.0036211810*0 + 0.0958378615*0 + 0.4912638747*10 + 1.9090575760*0 + -2.3437981117*0)/(1+exp(-8.2137089676 + 0.0004362439*20 + 0.0480655065*0 + 0.0123030656*260 + 0.0063869952*150 + 0.0036211810*0 + 0.0958378615*0 + 0.4912638747*10 + 1.9090575760*0 + -2.3437981117*0))
prob
## [1] 0.7036002
#According to our decision rules the only suitable rule is number 11, where DayMins=260, EveMins=150 and Call.center.Enquiry = 10, this means that the probability that a customer may churn is 96%.
#The decision rule based probability is higher than the one calculated by coeficients.
